d - and of course we - well, I mean, we just enjoyed life like that. I mean, I - I'm not going to say that - you know, we - we didn't see things, we didn't think, oh we'd like this and we'd like that, but we knew jolly well we couldn't have them, so we - 
w
e just went without. But then you see - everything - you see, you got so much value for what you did get, you see. Now for instance there was a penny bank in those days. Don't know if you've ever heard of the penny bank have you? Well - they liked you to 
save up - to about a shilling. Well of course - my money was - my - spending money was three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12347887\charrsid1069857  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
pence a week, I was the eldest you see, and the boys were tuppence and a penny the youngest one you see. Well I used to do errands for people in between - looking a
fter the - you know, from school and that sort of thing, and I used to generally make up to about - you know, probably a shilling a week altogether you see with my own three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12347887\charrsid1069857  }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 pence you see and I used to save this money, and do you know, I can't understand i
t now - but I used to actually save money in those days, and even when I started work - and I mean I start - when I started work I - I - I started work in a bankers shop. Which was half past seven in the morning 'til half past seven at night, we had of co
urse - periods in between when we had, you know, we had - had to have breakfast of course at that time and we had - our dinnertime and what}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12347887\charrsid1069857  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
