o
u see, but it was amazing you know how much - how much there was you know. And - you know, things like that. Now - and as regards sweets. I mean - well - the majority of sweets I mean you never - you never ever dreamt of - of spending - a penny - all at o
n
ce, in those days, because the sweets were four ounces a penny most of them you see. So - you - you probably spent a ha'penny and had a ha'penny back. And I remember once - one birthday of mine, somebody gave me a shilling. Well - I never had a shilling a
l
l at once to spend on, and they said to me, now you've got to spend it on - on what you want, you see. Well I think I told every child I knew - that I would treat them to sweets. Well - on the corner of - it - it's very very fashionable now, it's - it's a
 
very lovely house and I think somebody very very - well known has got it, and it was in Sheppell Place which is just off the Brompton Road, and there was two sisters, two old ladies, and they had this sweetie shop, and they were all in their glass jars yo
u
 know, all - it was really a lovely old shop you see, and of course I went in and so I said to them, it's my birthday today, and - I - I - and I've got these hoards of children, far too many that could get in - it was only a tiny shop you see. So I said, 
I
'll have - a ha'porth of those and a ha'porth of those, you see, and I hadn't realized really exactly what a shilling was you see, not then. And of course when I got you know, to about a dozen of these ha'porths of this and ha'porth of that, the old lady 
s
aid, what have - how much money have you got Freda, you see. So I said, oh I've got plenty of money, you see, and then I showed them this shilling. Well - finally I - I'd got so many children, you know, lined up, you know, about this sweet business, which
 - which I thought was going to be }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12347887\charrsid1069857 inexhaustible}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
 sort of thing, that in the end, I was left with one little - one little packet of sweets, that was - that was my - that was my birthday, because the children had disappeared, but I never forgot that. And I al
ways - always felt now - now - what - now you see that's what a lot of children miss today. You see, now what - actually what can they get today for a shilling. I mean, I don't know. Bar of chocolate probably or - two of those - gob-stoppers we used to ca
ll them and - and - things like - but - but - but that - but they don't know the joy of - of - of - of getting a penny and getting a ha'penny or three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12347887\charrsid1069857  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 farthings change. You see, even a farthing in those days was - I mean - you know, you got a farthing, well
 you've got money you see. And a ha'penny, I mean, you - you'd literally got wealth if you spent a farthing, you had a farthing back. You see, so that - really and truly - I think in a way although - I mean - as I say, wages and - and - and everything. Bu
t then you see, you did get value - for - for what you had. And you see, as regards food - I mean - you see, everything was - was so reasonable. And then of course you see there was none of this pre-packed stuff, or anything of that.
