Very very little. The only - the only thing that I remember tinned - when I was young, was tinned salmon which came out perhaps Christmas or somebody's birthday or something of that. And - and tinned pineapple. I remember
 that because - pineapple was one of the things, but - but - it used to be about three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12347887\charrsid1069857  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
pence ha'penny a tin. And the salmon would be about nine}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12347887\charrsid1069857  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
pence a tin. You see. But - but they were definite luxuries, I mean, they were things that - that - that you jus
t wouldn't have. But then you see, everybody cooked in those days. Everybody - you see I mean, of course I was lucky as I say my father - you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Who did the cooking in your house, your father or your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Well mother wasn't a - well, when 
I say she wasn't a very good cook - she didn't like cooking. Now I love cooking. I - I mean myself, you know, but - but - my mother could let my father do much cooking because he was too extravagant. You see, he never had to - I mean, he'd have barrels of
 
eggs, pounds of butter, he cooked everything with butter. Well, we - we - we couldn't - we couldn't - couldn't afford that. Best butter in those days was one and tuppence a pound I remember. And - of course margarine had - had just recently come on the ma
r
ket and of course we used to have to have it. But what I do remember - I remember dripping. And it was wonderful. And in - in the early days you know before they made - I don't know when it came out, I think it came out about 1912, there was a ruling that
 
- oh about children not going into public house you see. Well, in those days all the - little public houses round about, they always - always gave very good luncheons, which some of them do nowadays. But I mean it was a well known thing and I mean - a wor
k
ing man, if he was working away from home, would invariably go in a pub because he got a good meal. I think it was a shilling, but he got roast and - two vegetables and what have you. Yes, I think that was the - you know, the standard sort of price. Well 
o
bviously, in these places they had to have - probably three joints on, they'd probably have beef, lamb and pork, in season, you know, they'd have at least three things. Well they used to get lots and lots of dripping. We used to go with a basin, for this 
dripping. We were allowed - children were allowed to go into the pubs in those days, you know, in - you know, before the - and we used to go and it used to be three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12347887\charrsid1069857  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 pence a pound. And I used to get three or four pounds at a time, and we used to get it in - 
get it, used to run it down and then at the bottom there'd be this beautiful jelly. And I sat in front - I've sat in front with a whole pile of - of bread, 'cos there was no sliced - bread in those days you know, but whole pile of bread, sliced it up and 
-
 and - and had a - a fork, and you know I think there's nothing like the taste of toast - from a fire, a real fire, with dripping on it. And it's - it's one of the - it was one of our - our - our delights. We - we didn't want cake if we could have bread a
n
d dripping. And - and that's what we - but you see, they was - it was all the goodness, it was all - it - it was all wonderful you know. So that I mean - very cheaply you could - and then in - in those days they were the little - always the little corner 
shops, on every corner. Then if you weren't very well off, you know, or you hadn't got very much that week, well instead of buying a pot of jam you could go with a basin, you could get a pennyworth of jam. Or treacle. Or syrup.
