Well - no, Christmas - Christmas was always a very - a very strong - family affair. Well - we used to have - any relatives that happened to be near would probably look in, and then as I say there - there wouldn't be anything ela
borate, because my people - neither of them drank, you see, they weren't drinkers. But - we-d have - you know, sing-songs, which everybody - sort of entered in and all my mother's people were musical you see, and - we'd enter into that and then it would b
e
 - it would be sandwiches, I mean, if you had turkey well then there'd be turkey sandwiches, what have you. And then they usually finished up the - the time with - they were very fond of playing cards. Whist and - what have you you know and that sort of t
h
ing. And - and then that used to - used to go on and of course the men used to have their smokes and that and of course - I used to put the children to bed and of course - get myself to bed and then of course - I don't remember, but - we never had very - 
v
ery hectic times, but we always used to try to have - have a Christmas tree. Which we also got very cheaply you know. And - there used to be also a penny bazaar in the Brompton Road. It is now the - the - the place where they had the penny bazaar is now t
h
e International Stores. Now. Yes. Well opposite there, I don't know if you noticed, there's a - archway. Well through there, that was where we lived, that comes into the street, you should go round there sometimes, it's - it's most interesting. It's very 
