\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 No. No, we didn't - we didn't because mother wanted us all to have a little patch. But one of my little brothers, I must tell you, I had p
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12347887\charrsid1069857 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
rsevered with little packets of seed you know and - I'd got them coming up you see and - I bought - bought them each a packet you see and this one little boy you see, so he went out you see, and I - I showed him how
 to put them in you see, and of course mine had been in for some time you see and mine were coming up little shoots were coming and - and things and eventually flowers of course. So - every morning he used to go out and he used to say - used to kneel down
,
 he used to say, there's nothing coming up. There's nothing coming up. I said, oh you'll have to wait - we'll have to wait a bit Georgie, you know, it won't be - they won't be just yet. Well one day I'd got - oh quite an array of blooms on my patch of gar
d
en you see - and - I was very pleased about it, any rate I was doing some chores in - in the house, and - this young one was missing, he was about two and a half at the time. And - mother said, what on earth is - is he doing? She said, you'd better go and
 
have a look, she said, he's in the garden you see. So I said, oh he's watching the seeds come up, I said, he - he - if that's all he's doing he'll wait a long time, they won't be up for some weeks. Well when I went out I could have cried. There - was all 
m
y - blooms - sitting on the top of his little bit of garden. He said, they've come up. They've come up. Of course he knew he was very naughty and of course we had to - we had to sort of convince him that it was wrong in case he ever went into anybody's ga
r
den, you know, and did it. But - you know, you - you just couldn't hit them really. You know, it was - it was just one - I - I - I don't think - you know, our parents, we were very - very seldom hit. I mean we had to be very very naughty to get a - I mean
,
 I don't say there weren't - we weren't naughty sometimes and mischievous but - I mean, we had to be - really do something really - really bad you know. And - and - and another thing I remember once - when - we were in the museum - mind he was a very beau
t
iful child, I think I've shown you the photograph of him. And everybody used to remark, he had most beautiful - golden hair you see which curled naturally you see. And - it wasn't much good keeping a cap on it because it was springy, you know, springy cur
l
s. And - one day we were - in the museum and - wandering round you know, we'd been round for some time, and - there were - two Americans, lady and a gentleman, coming through you see. So they - they remarked you know, the gentleman first remarked and so s
h
e said, oh yes, hadn't he got - you know, beautiful hair. And he was used to - you know, people saying this you see. So - so she said, is that - is that one of your little brothers, you see. So I said, yes, the other one - I'd got two of them with me then
,
 the other one had wandered off onto a case or something. So - so she said, oh, she said, and have you - have you got any sisters? So I said, oh no, I haven't got any sisters, I'm - the only girl you see. So - anyway after a lot of talking, you know, and 
-
 and one thing and another, she said, how old is he? So I said, well he's two and a half. And he was a very big child, he was twelve pound ten when he was born, which was enormous. My mother was a very small person. Much smaller than me. And - he - he was
 
really a lovely child. So - any rate - after he'd gone - this lady - turned round, and - she put a half a crown in - in - this child's - little hand you see. So of course we'd always been told we must never, you know, like take money and things like that 
y
ou see. So I said, oh - you know. So she said. Oh yes, she said, you - you - now you must buy - buy something, she said, you want, you know. Any rate - off they went you see. Oh, so - when they'd gone you see, he still clutched this so I said, now give me
 
the money Georgie. So he said, the lady said I was - you was to spend it on us, you see. So I said, yes, I will, but give it me - for now, I thought - a whole half a crown, I wasn't - just going to spend on them anyway. So - then he looked at me, and he a
l
ways thought you know, I was - you know, everything I said was - you know, was it you see. And - so he said, you told a story. So I said, told a story? Why? He says, you told that lady you hadn't got any sisters. I said, well I haven't got any sisters. An
d
 you said you'd got two brothers. He said. I've only got one brother. You see. So I said, yes, I know. But I said, you've got a sister. So he said, well I can't have a sister if you haven't got a sister. You see, that was his way of reasoning. Well, yes, 
well any rate, I bought - you know, about two}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12347887\charrsid1069857  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
penn'orth of sweets or what have you for we got home, you see, I changed the half a crown. And I gave two shillings of it back - to mother you see. 'Cos I thought well naturally she could - used it much better t
han us and we'd had these sweets you see which were a bonus for us you see. So - he couldn't contain himself any longer so he said - mum, our Freda tells - tells stories. So - good gracious, does she, whatever has she done? So of course he repeated this. 
A
nd you know, it was a long long time before we could make - so he said, well, he said, she has got a sister, she's got her. She's got herself you see. And - oh it was a long time before we could make that child, you know. Well - my mother was very ill som
e
time after that and I - I first started - you see, I used to have to step away from school. Well in those days you had what they called the - board school man come round you see, you know. So I said, well, I said, I can't - I can't come to school because 
t
hese children are too young. So this very child - he actually was accepted at school when he was two and a half. Well he died at four and a half, well he - you know. So he had two years of schooling. And do you know, that - when he went to school that chi
l
d could write his name, he could draw, he could - you know, I - I think he would have been a very very intelligent child you know if he'd have lived. But of course you see - you know, when you've got others in the same - the family to help and that sort o
f
 thing, you see, so the - the - the headmistress, it was only a small school as I tell you - she accepted us because - otherwise it meant me - stopping away from school you see because in those days you never had any help - if - if you had illness, or, yo
u
 know, you had your - there was nobody - nobody did anything you see. And of course - my father couldn't always - sometimes he could be home 'cos sometimes he did dinners at night you see, but then - he couldn't choose what he was going to do, he had to d
o
 what - he could do sort of thing you see. So that very often you see, if he was - if he was doing dinners at night it was all right because he could be in in the day and he could help and he would - look to the children you see, but you see, you couldn't
 
guarantee that you see, so that that's why I - I - you know, I stopped away from school. But only for a little while because you know they were so insistent, but any way I left school when I was fourteen, and - and - and - and got a job. You see because I
