 in you see, you kept the range in your see. So it was - it was rather wonderful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Did you always have a lodger in the houses you lived in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Well more or less.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 You lived in about four or five didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Yes. Oh yes, we did. Yes, more or
 less, yes, because as I say we - we mostly had a six roomed house you see, that's the way the houses were built you see, and of course - you know, to - to pay the rent and - you know, to - sort of - go - you know, I mean. It was - it was more or less nec
essary really you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Why did you move from house to house in those times?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
Oh, I don't know, I suppose it was - just - well I mean we didn't - we didn't move every five minutes you know, I can only remember about - I suppose about six moves in
 the whole of my life you know. Until - I think we had far more moves from the - from the beginning of the last war - 'til - you know, through the bombing and what have you you know. Much more. But of course we - we - we never have - in those days you kno
w you - you wouldn't have lived in a place like this. You - you'd reckon to be very poor to live in a place like this. Now I'm jolly glad to be living here. You know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Would you change houses because your father had got another job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Well sometimes
, sometimes but then you see - even that didn't - didn't - present any problem to dad because he'd got his bike, because - you see he wouldn't - he wouldn't have minded if it was an hour away, if it was - if it was a good job. He - he wouldn't think of an
 hour and an hour back as a - anything. You know, with the bike, I mean he wouldn't - he wouldn't think of it in terms like that. So that - you know, one thing - balanced another.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Did you ever have any relatives living with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 No. No. No, all our relatives were better off than us you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 They lived quite near really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
No, not really near, no, not - really near. Had one relative - a brother of my mother's that lived in - in Pimlico at one time, he was a musician.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 How often would you see relatives?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
Oh - two or three times a year I suppose, something like that, but mother did have for - for quite a considerable time, she did have a - a younger brother of hers living with her. He was a musician. He never ever married. He - he di
ed when he was about forty-two. And - he was - he was one of the original - and funny I heard it on the - television the other night, he was one of the original members of Paul Whiteman's band. Yes. And he went out to America to - you know, with - with Pa
ul Whiteman. He - he - ended up as - bandmaster of the Sussex Showmanry - of course she had four brothers, there were four girls and four boys you see, and they were - they were all musical you see, they were all the - all the - all the boys were musical.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 You say that the mother and father were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
Well - grandfather was you see, he was a minstrel at night you see. And of course he was an umbrella maker during - with his shop during the day you see, but of course having - having this family, because 
it was very sad, he had a - a train accident, he - he - he - my - my - grandmother was a widow at thirty - with eight children. Wasn't a very -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 So you never knew your grandfather at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Grandfather, no I never knew him, no, no. But I think my 
mother took after him, he was a little man you see. 'Cos when people used to tease him about grandma being such a - what they call a fine woman you know, so he said, oh well, he liked plenty for his money sort of thing you know and he liked to be - you kn
o
w - but - he was - he was a very - very advanced man for his time I think you know. Very - very much so, he was very keen on education. Two of her brothers went to St Marks College. You know, the Fulham Road, well - part's in Fulham Road and part's in - K
i
ngs Road. They went to St Marks College. Two of her brothers. But of course in those days you see again you see, it was the boys that was considered to be - to get - well - I mean, they - they sort of - you see, girls in those days either went into servic
e
, you see, and then got married young you see, that - that - that was what there was for girls you see, I mean, you didn't - I mean, shop life you know, was - was considered very - you know - down you know sort of thing you know, but - of course mother wa
s always - always a bit of a singer and when she was quite a - quite a small child she sang to Queen Victoria, and I'm always sorry that that went in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid721979\charrsid1069857 bits}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 , and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Was it a record of it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 No, no. No. She sang to her personally you know - on the 
top of Constitution Hill you see, well of course Queen Victoria was quite an old - you know, getting quite old then, and - any rate mother said the thing that frightened her was, you see,; there was - all her class there and they sang, you know first of a
l
l, well then the solo mother had to sing on her own you see. And she stood on this little platform well then the - don't know if it was the Chancellor or who ever it was with the - with the Queen you know, beckoned her to come forward and she was terrifie
d to go because of these prancing horses, she was terrified of horses.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 You say you had a wash house out the back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Would you do the washing out there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Oh mother would, oh yes. Oh yes, you had to, yes, and of course you had your 
garden, you had your line - line of clothes and of course everything got - you know, and of course -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Did she ever have anyone come in to help clean up the house and things?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Well - well - when she - she was at times very ill you see, she wasn't 
a very strong person, although she lived to a great age - and - she used to have a - a - there's an old lady, we called her Old Tilly, and she used to come, she used to go to various people's places, and she come for what they call the day, I think she co
me for half a crown a day and her dinner, you know, that was the - thing in those days. Well then, - she'd do - she'd do a proper wash, everything you know, sheets and you know the whole lot you know. And she'd be out there and then, you know, mother }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid721979\charrsid1069857 wo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 u}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid721979\charrsid1069857 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 d 
send me out with cups of tea or glass of beer I think she had you know, jug of beer, 'cos as I say children were allowed to go and get it for her in between and then of course we'd call her in and then she'd have her dinner with us, you know, round the ta
ble in the kitchen, you know, we had a big kitchen table you know. And - and then - she'd go on 'til about four or five you know, and then - a cup of tea and then - you know, something -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 What day of the week would this be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Usually on a Monday, Mo
nday was generally wash day, yes, and of course somehow or other the weather used to be different in those days somehow, we used to get - as I was saying to someone the other day you know, you - you always got proper sort of summers and winters and I can 
r
emember - you know, I can remember you know very very deep in snow you know and - and - and - and the snow settling and stopping you know, I can - I can remember that very plainly as a - as a child, but - 'course it never seems to happen nowadays. Well I 
t
hink - well I think so. They laugh at me but I say it's because it's - it's all this - you know, nonsense up above, all this nuclear business you know. And - they - they - they all say that it - it - it's nonsense but I don't know, I'm - I'm pretty sure i
t
 is, we never had it before. You could pretty - you could pretty well judge the weather you know and I mean of course children - more or less you see, you were - you were sort of - penalized about holidays in a way because you see - you sort of more or le
s
s had to go away when the children had school holidays you see, that was the - that was the point. But as I say, we - we didn't - we didn't have - lots of holidays. But we had lots of day out, you see, that was - that was our way, but I don't think we rea
lly missed it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Would there be paid holidays for your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
Oh I don't think so in those days, no, I don't - no because you see he did - well Bank Holidays he was mostly working you see. You see, he did - he did this what they called more or les
s casual type of work you see, I mean - the force of - you see any hotel or - that type of thing, it's - it's - it's totally different you see, it's - it's - it is casual you see, it's not a - as I say it's not a - a definite - you see, I think that's why
 
- you know - other people in the family thought - you know, my mother hadn't done the right thing, you know, dad hadn't - you see - my father was very nice man but he was - you see, my mother would have had the push and she would have the go-ahead to do t
h
ings, but my father was - if it's possible he was sort of too contented, you see, if he just got enough that was all right for dad you see. He wasn't - he wasn't so ambitious that he wanted to do - you know, I think he could have done much more than he di
d
, you know what I mean. I don't think he - I think he sort of - under-rated himself you know, more than - was really necessary you see, but you see - what he did - enabled him to go off and do what he wanted and he - he felt that that was all right and no
body ought to grumble. And as mother never grumbled you know, I mean, she just sort of accepted it, he never interfered with what she wanted to do, providing - that I - or somebody else did it you see, I mean - so -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Do you think both of them gave you the ideas of what things to consider important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
Oh well - I think I can - achieve something from both of them really, you know what I mean. I mean - you know - that - both my mother and father, they all - all had a dread, I think people did i
n those days, of sort of hire purchase and things like that I mean, we was always taught that - you must have - they'd be horrified with me because I hire this, but - I feel that anyone in position you know, to buy a television, you know, and you don't kn
o
w much about it - I mean anybody can come in and tell you - that - things are gone, you know, whether they have or not and it can be a very expensive business, that was the reason why I did it. But apart from that I mean - I would never think - I would ne
v
er think for instance of having a - a suit or a dress or anything like that or - or furniture or anything on hire purchase, never. And I think that's been instilled in me you see, we were always taught that you - you save for what you wanted and - and - t
hen when you saved it you got it, you see, that was the thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Did they give you pocket money when you were young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 No, I say, I - I used to have about three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid721979\charrsid1069857  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 pence a week, when - of course when dad wasn't earning I didn't have it. But I used to make it up because I used to do errands for people you see and get tuppence here and tuppence there and that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 What kind of people did you do errands for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Oh, anybody that wanted them, and - mostly people that hadn't got children to d
o them, 'cos people that had children didn't - didn't reckon to pay you to do their errands you see. But of course - it was - it was hard tack in those days you know. And - one of my brothers, he used to do a paper round. And his paper round was - in Knig
h
tsbridge and he used to do all the Officers in Knightsbridge barracks. And he was - they all called him Curly, 'cos he had curly hair too like the other one, and - he was - he was very popular, but I think it was about five shillings a week you know. But 
of course he - he - he used - but of course that was no - no bother getting up early because - I mean, you - you got up early in those days you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 What time would you have breakfast in those days?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Well you'd have - have breakfast when he finis
hed his round you see, he - he'd - he'd - I generally used to make him up - about half past six you see, to go you see, and I'd - I'd have a - you know, a sandwich or something ready for him and a cup of milk, we didn't have tea, not when we were very you
ng. And - off he'd go. Well when he came in about - half past eight or nine, you see, then he'd have his breakfast, well then I - I'd cook him a breakfast you see. And go to school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 What kind of thing would you have for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Oh well, depend
s what we'd got you know. Scrambled eggs usually, 'cos I used to get what they called cracked eggs which you got cheaper, you took a basin, and - you got about - seven for three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid721979\charrsid1069857  }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 pence was the current - you know - rate in those days -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Where would your mother bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
She'd probably be at work, yes. Yes, she'd probably be at work, so I - I mostly did - well, it - it - it depended what - what time it was you see. So that I got used to, you know, sort of doing things like that. Well I did sort of simple 
things you know. I mean - the kids had to have what I - I - I - I got sort of thing you know. Used to get one or two grumbles but not very much 'cos I used to try and work in - things that I knew that they - they would like you know. I mean we used to get
 
a lot of grumbles, you know, I don't want greens and I don't want this, that and the other, and I said, well you've got to have them because they're good for you, you know, and - if you don't have 'em you can't have your pudding and that sort of thing. An
d that's the way we did in those days. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Where would you have the meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
Oh in the kitchen. Oh yes, we always had - well you see in those days you had a big kitchen with a dresser, with all the things on it. And - you know - a nice fire an
d what have you you know and it was always - I always think the most comfortable place in the house, I mean, as I say the parlour was for visitors chiefly, and if you weren't very well - you were laid up in the parlour in state for the doctor to call on y
o
u you know. And what have you. But - on the whole it was - I - I - I've got no complaints - really and truly. I mean - I don't think - I - I think - we were - you know - in our time, I think we were much happier than the people are nowadays. I do honestly
. I - I think that. And I think it was because well we - you know, I mean - it isn't - it was no good grumbling. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Do you ever remember being conscious that your parents had a struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Oh yes, very often. Oh I was very cons
cious of - of that you see, and all the time, all - you know all my very young life, you know I can - always - always remember - thinking about - like the price of anything before I'd - I - you know ever suggest it you see. Other children might say, oh we
l
l, you know, we want so and so and so and so, but - and of course the boys would say that you see but - I would say, oh no - mum can't afford that, oh we can't have that. Oh no, you can't have that, no. No, well, I'll speak to dad tonight and I'll ask him
 
what we can have for a change from milk - you know, 'cos milk pudding didn't go down too well you know every day you know. And - and then - when apples were very cheap you know and - then I got the idea, you know, from dad about an apple charlotte you kno
w
 and I used to put the jam in first and then the fruit and then the bread - bread. Well he used to tell me you see - of course he used to tell my mother but she used to say, oh I know what to do, you know, another of your expensive ideas. But - you see, i
f
 you listened to dad it wasn't all that expensive but you see, my - my mother wasn't - well - she didn't like cooking, I mean, I couldn't say she couldn't cook because she could, but - she didn't like it, and I mean - to really - to - you know, to - to re
a
lly do cooking you've got to like it I think, you have. And I did like it. And of course I used to do - what my mother used to call - she used to say, oh we don't want all the embellishments, and I mean if we had a trifle you know, we had - used to get so
m
e stale - sponge cake you know, or we had some stale cake left you know and we used to make it up in that and of course - I always used to have to decorate it with a few - nuts and cherries and something on the top you see. Mother would simply - slap the 
c
ustard on top and there it was you see. But - mother didn't think that was necessary but of course - you see, I was a bit like my father there you see, of course, I mean in that - in - the hotel world and that sort of thing, I mean, the visual look of the
 
thing is - is the things isn't it you see, and of course I used to - you know, and I used to go to all this trouble to - put these things on the top and - and - and do this you see, and - and of course it used to look - it used to look nice. Mother said, 
o
h we haven't got time for that, you know. But - she wasn't an impatient woman by any means, but it was just that - she didn't think it was necessary you see and - of course we - we just used to - used to take it you know and of course sometimes she'd say 
t
o me - you going to make the pudding tomorrow? I said, yes I'll make it. You see, so then I used to do it, you know. That sort of thing, but - oh we got - we - we got on all right, I think we were very - you know, we were very happy family really you know
.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 You sound very close to both your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
Well I think - I think we were really, and - well, for the last fifteen years I'm very thankful to say that neither of my parents - and of course another thing they had a dread - a dread of, which of 
course was rather silly and I had to talk to - and it was only the last five years of their - their life that - that I ever got them to - to accept any supplementary or anything you know. They - they thought - in their way it was charity, you see, and I h
a
