\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Did you have different clothes to wear on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
Oh yes. Yes, oh yes, we always - it was - it was very necessary in those days, we always had - what we called our Sunday - clothes you know, and of course when they got - li
ttle bit old, of course then they got - you know, we took them for weekdays and then when we had anything new it was - first of all it was Sunday clothes, and they were worn on Sundays, oh yes. Majority of people, you know - ordinary working class people 
l
ike ourselves - I mean, did adhere to that you know. And there wasn't so much - people - I mean majority of children played in the streets, we didn't - very much because we weren't allowed to, but - majority of children did, but on Sundays - the mothers s
eemed to have that sort of, you know, oh well, you mustn't - play today, it's Sunday, sort of things you see, and - well of course - children, you know, of that - that era - well I mean, more or less did listen to their - parents you know, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Were you allowed to play on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
Well - well - not exactly play. I think mostly - mostly Sundays - we - I used to sort of read to them and that sort of thing you know. 'Cos we used to go to Sunday school as I say and - come back from Sunday school and,
 you know, have - you know - a meal and what have you, well then - in the early days of course I mean - you know, you went to bed fairly early you see. No, I don't think - no, Sundays we never - you know. I was - oh I was quite grown up before I ever - ev
e
r thought of - going anywhere other than church, and then - I - I - occasionally used to go, they used to have what they - concerts, what they called Sunday League concerts, don't know if ever you've heard of them. Well - they were very - very - very nice
,
 they used to have them in - well, used to have them at the Chelsea Palace or - any big hall you know, and they were sort of in the old ballad days you know, when you get, you know, you get somebody - like - Indian love lyrics and - things of that kind yo
u
 know, or - if you got a - if you got a baritone or a bass you'd get - Company Sergeant Major and things of that kind, but - they were sort of - that - that type of singer you see, and - you'd - you'd have that and of course there was always an orchestra 
o
f course, there was no canned music in those days. There was always the orchestra and - they'd play band pieces and probably Gilbert and Sullivan and - what have you and things, it - it was very nice, it was about a couple of hours on a Sunday, it was onl
y
 about a shilling to go. And they used to call it - Sunday League Concerts. And - and they - they - they were very pleasant, very nice, but there was never anything rowdy or never anything - it wasn't like the music hall affair you see, 'cos that was Sund
ay you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Did you ever go to those?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
Oh yes, used to go to the music hall, yes, when I could, when I got a bit older, oh yes, used to go quite a lot. Oh yes, used to be marvellous because you see, all my life I - I had heard - all these old musi
c hall songs and - lots of people thought I was much older than I was because I mean I knew - I knew all the songs because I had - I had heard them right from - you know - early childhood you see, I - I - I knew them off by heart and I - I knew them prope
r
ly too. Yes. But they were wonderful - wonderful times you know, when I think nowadays I mean, when I - when I - I see the people with the microphones and that sort of thing, they never needed any microphones in those days and - and I mean - they - well -
 
well they just were heard and - and they had to be you know, they had to be good you know. Oh yes. I think it's a great - a great pity that the old music halls - have disappeared. Yes, I used to remember the old Holborn Empire, used to go up there sometim
e
s, 'cos this was when I was much older, I mean, you know, when I was about - sixteen, something like that you know. Mother and I used to go, because it was - it was all - it was all fairly - very cheap I mean, you know, you - you get on the bus to Holborn
 
and - you know, or a tube, and - I mean we always went - up in the gods, which I think was the - of course they say the - they - they used to have their best critics up there because - they really - you know, they really told them that - but then on the o
ther, hand, I mean when they were good, which they mostly all were, you know, I mean - you know }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15597842\charrsid1069857 - they - they just went on appl}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
auding, I mean it was nothing for them to come back five and six times you know, you - you'd probably - there'd probably be twenty
 turns on the bill you know, but - it was - you know, well packed, but of course if - if there was anything they didn't like I mean, you know, they were very quick to - to let them know and - and then of course they made a hasty retreat but - if they thou
g
ht they were - a sort of a - I think - I think the ordinary British public you know, are really very - very good in lots of ways you know, because if they thought they were very nervous I - I - I remember once seeing - the sort of a juggling act, I wasn't
 
very keen on that sort of thing but it was one of the things you know, and - one of the fellows, whether it was his first time on or - whether he was just learning or what you know he - he - he - he - he flicked and made a - you know, missed, you see. And
 
- you know, instead of - sort of - jeering or - you know, well you know - you know, they - they sort of - well you know, well of course the next time round he did it and he did it all right, there were two or three of them in this - thing you; know, and -
 
he did it all right, but - I - I think - they're - they're rather - rather kind to sort of - you know, if you do make a - make - make a slip - you know, and he was very young and - probably, you know, it was his - but - oh, they still - and at the end the
y got the applause and - you know, just the same as if they - if they done everything right through perfectly you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 What about things like circuses and fun fairs, were they around then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Yes, there were some circus - circuses, I think - I thin
k the Bertram Mills was around. But - we - we didn't - you - you didn't see much of those at the ordinary music halls. No, used to have to go to Olympia or - or somewhere like that, but it used to be a once a year - thing, you know. No, I didn't very ofte
n
 go, because - I don't know, I used to be a bit frightened. I once saw an accident - once, on - on - you know - that - that was also that was a Japanese, it was - one of these high wire things and they had it from the stage, and we were in the gallery, an
d
 he - he walked - you know - tight walked - rope walk - walked, and the thing was suspended to the top you see and I believe he'd been doing it all the week and this was about the middle of the week, and - as he - he got almost to the gallery which was qu
i
te a long way from the stage you see and he'd got this umbrella you know to balance himself - something must have gone wrong, you see, and he slipped. Well - that man's face, I can remember, because it came very very near to where I was sitting, which I'd
 
got my usual seat in the front row, and underneath the - the greasepaint and - what have you - I could see the - the - horror - or the - in his eyes you know. And - of course he - he - he - he went - he flipped back and he fell onto the stage you see, and
 
- they pulled the curtain down and got a doctor and - I suppose and took him off. Well then the next act was put on you know, they didn't stop for long. And - any rate the manager came out and he said that he's being attended and everything was all right,
 
but I had an awful funny feeling that - you know - everything wasn't all right you know. It - it was just - just because you see, I - I suppose he suddenly realized that something was wrong you se, and - and he just couldn't make it you see. If he hadn't 
h
ave been up so high he probably - if he'd have been in - around by the pit or the stalls you see he could probably - be in a - you know, he could probably have sort have - balanced and - and jumped and - and - and not hurt, but you see, right up in the go
d
s which was - you know, very high up, he - he couldn't do much about it and I - I should imagine he broke his back, I don't know but - it - no - we never really heard about it, but - well of course I suppose it's not good - policy anyway, but in any case 
i
t - it sort of put me off you know, I was quite young at the time, but I - I was very impressed with that you know, and - I thought no, I don't want to see them, so - if ever I did go, it - other times you know and there was one of these turns on which th
e
re were sometimes, I used to always shut me eyes, if - if it was anything coming up you know, to - you know, I used to shut me eyes and I used to say to the others, now - has he gone, is it over, you know, they used to say, yes it's all right and then I -
 I didn't used to watch that, because - I think it's - it's just one of those things that - that happens to you you can't help it's just something that - that happens.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 You say your mother was a good singer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Your brothers were in a choir, were you ever in the church choir at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
Oh yes. Oh yes, I was, because - in - in - in some churches you know they used to have - girls and women, you know, and I - I've got quite a - quite a few certificates for singing and - and what have yo
u. Oh yes I was very fond of singing you know. And I was always yanked out at school you know, to - take part in - and of course I was very lucky you see, because - my mother knowing quite a bit about singing and - this uncle that lived with us that - was
 
- was a musician you see, and of course he used to take me through - through the music part of it you see and - and of course I used to get that and of course - when - when I went back, I mean, most of the children only had - a little tuition from the tea
c
her you see, well - I mean, when we were doing - you know, when you're doing a school play, well of course - when - especially the little children I mean all the mothers and fathers come you know, or the mothers anyway you see, well I mean, they all appla
u
d whether little Johnny, you know, gets up and makes a mess of it or not, I mean everybody - you know - so - it's all pretty good - but the teacher used to be very pleased with me you see because - you see, I - I had more tuition than - most of the childr
e
n, you see, and I - 'course I used to get my notes perfect you see, that was - that was the thing you see, so of course, if you - if you got that part of it all right, I mean the song comes - easily to you you see, so really - I suppose really in a way it
 
wasn't really fair in one way, but - of course they were very pleased because it - you know, it sort of - you know, after all the - singing teacher was very pleased if she got somebody she could sort of - show off to the - you know, to the - rest of the s
chool you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 You say you did plays and things at the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
Oh yes. Plays. Oh yes. Oh yes. Well we did - oh, they were very ambitious in those days for us kids you know, used to - do bits of Shakespeare and what have you, I don't know that w
e were always - you know, word perfect in that but - it used to go through and as I say - it went down pretty well you know, the - most of the audience of course were our - but - but - of course we - we used to have quite a - quite a few local people, big
-
wigs that used to come you know and of course - they used to very politely applaud and they used to sort of present the prizes and what have you you see to us. But - it all went down very well. Well I think on the whole you know, -we we didn't do too badl
y for a little - little school you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Did your parents go to the school much or take much interest in what you were doing there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Oh yes, yes, we used to get - get the usual - you know, notes to take home you know and - if - you know, if we wer
en't doing very well you know, it used to be, you know - spoken of you see, and - and that sort of thing, but - they used to sort of ask - I suppose ask our - our parents, you know, what, you know, they would like us, you know, to do, you know, later on -
 
in life, but of course - we never had any what I call - any fancy learning. Anything that I learnt otherwise - I used to go to evening classes when I was - when I had left school you see, and I went to evening classes, just here - in the Marlborough - sch
ool.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Evening classes in what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
Well, I - I - I wanted to learn - learn - I started to learn French. And we were very lucky there because they had - noted teachers, a very old lady and her daughter. They - they both used to teach French, one used t
o teach - teach, you know, first year students and the other one used to teach them more advanced students you know. And - you know, it was - it was just - it was something extra to learn, but you had to take two subjects always you see. So the other - th
e
 other subject that went with French which I - I didn't feel I'd have any use for, was commercial correspondence, which I had to take - as a compulsory subject to - to learn the French you see. Oh I think it was only about half a crown a term in those day
s that one paid so you could afford it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 How old would you be when you took these classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 About fifteen. I left school at fourteen and - I - left school just after I was fourteen you see. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 How many evenings a week was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Oh only
 once a week. Once a week, I think it was a Wednesday, two hours. Two hour periods they were, seven 'til nine they used to be in those days. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Did you go for one year or two years?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Oh one or two years I think I did, you know, in various thin
gs. Of course you could take on all sorts of things you know - but - I didn't - I didn't seem to thing that anything else would - you know, would really be necessary in a way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 This was while you were working in the bakers shop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Yes, I started - 
I started out in life - well I started out in life at Harrods actually. I went into the Counting House when I - when I first left. But - they used to - they used to come to the school every so often to know how many people were leaving, and then they used
 
to set us a small exam, you see, well I mean, everybody more or less passed unless they were absolutely you know - very lazy or very you know - uneducated and - and then you went. But of course it was - in those days it was quite a thing to be - be taken 
on, you know. They didn't take everybody, and they were very particular - I mean - of course such things couldn't be now, they used to go through - you know - who your parents were and - your grandparents and - this sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 So they came to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
Oh - oh - well they used to come and - you see, every - every now and again you see, that was the nearest school you see, and I suppose they knew there'd be children leaving, they were always looking out for - for school leavers, and of course that i
s one thing about Harrods, they have a very good system there for teaching youngster. And once you've been to Harrods and gone through their - you know, their - you - you - you can always get a job anywhere. Because they know that if you've had that train
ing that you must have - you know, you must have been - fairly good or - or you wanted have gone through it you see. And - but of course they weren't - they weren't all that good prayers you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 How much did you get in that job then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Well I got five shillings a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 For how many hours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
Oh - I think I used to work - I believe I used to work from half past eight - the shop didn't open 'til nine, but that didn't affect any - anything, I mean, you - you had to get there before that, hal
f past eight I think to about six I think it was in those days. And - of course Saturdays you were off at one o'clock, you know. And in the early days too they used to - they used to always supply our food. We used to get food you see, and of course havin
g no fares to pay you see - it was all right, so I was able to give my mother half a crown a week out of five shillings a week, and able to buy myself odd things which I had to get you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 This would just be a midday meal you'd get would it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Yes, a midday - oh yes, they didn't reckon to give us tea because we - we finished they reckoned, you know, in time to get tea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 How long were you there for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 I was there in the the first instance for about three - three and a half years, then I got 
a transfer, I went to Dickens and Jones which belongs to Harrods in Regent Street. And - I was there for - quite a few years. Well then I went back to Harrods afterwards - to learn millinery. I was an apprentice in the millinery department.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 How old would you be then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
About - let's see, fourteen, seventeen - oh be about eighteen, nineteen I suppose. But then I left and I went into the - into the bakery - business - you know, line, which was very hard work, half past seven 'til half past seven, wit
h appropriate times off in between you know for meals. But - strang}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15597842\charrsid1069857 el}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
y enough it - it - it seemed to agree with me, the - - I like people you see and I like to - I liked the shop life. You see, when I was apprenticed you see you only had the - people - you
 know, at the table - the milliner and other people and that sort of thing and you were sort of - and - and - and when I was in the Counting House you see you were in an office and you were enclosed with - well a dozen people say or something of that kind
. But I liked - I like people and - of course the shop life suited me. But I was very delicate as a child, I used to have - very bad faints, I - I - I left - almost every job I had for health reasons.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 How long were you in the bakers shop for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Oh 
quite a few years, quite a few, I got up to be manageress. And - you know, learnt quite a lot about it - you know, it's not just all - you see when you're manageress you see you're responsible for - if there's a baker - yes, not only that - you're respons
i
ble for - all the ordering of goods, you see, the - of course there'd - there'd be a foreman baker who would do all the bread and - and - and things of that kind. Well then there'd be pastry cooks you see who would do the - the cakes and what have you and
 
- and of course - usually we had - usually - usually - usually a foreigner we had that - that was - used to do all the spectacular icing and things of that kind, and of course I used to love to go down when they were - they were doing things, and of cours
e
 he didn't mind you know and - used to like to watch you know, I think it was - you know, that sort of thing I - I had a - had a liking for it. Well then you see you had to - you had to order - all the things, they would give you a list and then you had t
o
 sort of work things out - and - it - it was quite a - you know, it's quite a tricky job really to do, but - I liked it, I - I thought it was very nice. 'Course things are much easier these days, although of course - there - there's so little - little hom
e
 baked - bread about these - these days, you see it's all pre-packed and it's all oven - done up, you know, from - straight from the bakeries that - that one doesn't see you see, in those days there were about twenty different kinds of - of bread. Differe
n
t kinds of loaves to - remember, you know, fro one thing, and - as I say, the first thing we had to do - first thing in the morning we had to put all these - loaves on the scales and weigh them, and if they didn't weigh, you see, we either rejected them, 
p
ut them in a separate thing, and sold them cheaply, you know. Or - we put this - sort of - biscuits or what - what have you as - as make weight you see, that - that's still went on - that - that still went on in - round about 1917, something like that you
 know, when I was - you know, doing it. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 How would you get on with your employers in the Harrods job and the bakers shop to begin with before you became a manageress?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Well - oh all right. All right, yes, you know, I always - I was always wi
lling to - you know, to have a go and - you know, they - they - they were always - you know, glad for anyone that would - do, you see, I didn't mind, I used to - but of course there's quite a lot of book keeping and of course - that - that wasn't my stron
g
 point at - at school, I wasn't - I wasn't all that good at - arithmetic and things like that, and it's very funny, all through my life I've had to do it quite a lot. I've got on with it but - it - it - it wouldn't have been what I would have chosen you k
n
ow, if - if I - I'd had my way. But - I never - I - I - the only prizes I - I won at school were - were for English. Now I always wanted to write. And - I used to - I used to get - I used to be - during - during the first world war - there used to be one 
p
erson out of every class and I was chosen for our class - to write - we used to write to prisoners of war, we used to write to interned sailors or - anybody that was interned you know in countries you see, and of course first of all, I - I used to write m
o
re or less what the teachers had said you know, then after a bit you know I thought, well, you know, a lot of these, they're only young men you know, 'cos I was only a kid myself, I was only about eleven or twelve, but - I used to think, well I don't thin
k
 they want to know all this, so I used to get my brothers to tell me all the local - football news and what have you, and you see I used to put all this in the - in the letters you see. And after a bit my letters weren't vetted they used to go straight aw
a
y you see in the first case they were - the teacher used to sort of read them out. Well of course, back used to come these replies and of course they - they were evidently what the fellows wanted to know. They - you know - they wanted to know - I mean, fo
r
 instance - if they happened to live in Chelsea - well naturally they were Chelsea fans you see and of course my brothers - I didn't know much about football or anything - like that, but you see they used to tell me these - various names you see and I use
d
 to put in, you know, so and so and so and so and they - they beat you know another team whatever it was you see, well then of course if the fellows - belonged to the team that they beat or - you know, what have you you know, they used to be more interest
e
d in them and I used to get the - used to get back no end of letters you see, well one - one day - when - they used to go to the school of course, didn't come to me, and - one day one; came and the teacher was reading this out you see so she said, oh, she
 
said, I didn't know you wrote about all these things. I said, well - I - I thought - I thought Miss that - you know, that's what they wanted you see. So she said, well - yes, I suppose so, but - she said - you want to keep a bit to other things you see. W
e
ll then - I remember once - we - of course you wouldn't remember but you've probably heard of it, there was a very - famous escape from the submarine E13, the - well - the Captain o this you see, that - that escaped, you see, he got to London, he was deco
rated by - the Queen, well - strangely enough I suppose - way back in his mind he thought, well - I'll go}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15597842\charrsid1069857  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
to that school, you know, and see - you see, so he came to the school and he saw the headmistress, he said, now, he said, I want to see the little girl
 that - you - that wrote and kept up the morale of our men you know, because being an officer he was treated - you know, rather - and being interned it wasn't quite so bad as being in a prison camp, apart from they didn't have their freedom you see. And -
 
so of course I was brought forward you see. So he said, now you can ask me anything you like, and he'd just come from the investiture at Buckingham Palace. So I said, well what I would really like to know is, how you really did escape. Not what I've read 
a
bout, what you really did. And he burst out laughing and he told me. And he asked the headmistress if he could take me out to tea. And - of course he was a man about thirty - odd you know, any rate he took me out to tea and - had quite a nice - nice time,
 
but - but he - he told the headmistress then - he said, well, he said, you know, he said, it's very strange, he said, because, he said, I thought it was a young - you know, a - a sort of - well I suppose a - a sort of - different type of school you know, 
a
nd he thought I was about seventeen, you see, by my letters you see, he thought I was one of these young ladies, this school, and when he found out I was quite a little girl and - I was never very big for my age you know and I looked a little girl, he was
 
- he was most surprised, but he said that really and truly, the things that in my childish way I - you know, interested me I suppose, were - he said really were really more or less the things that they - they really wanted to hear you know. And it sort of
 
made them feel that, you know, people were - you know, interested. So of course the headmistress give me a look you know and of course after that I was allowed to - I - still went on writing you know and then we used to save up - save up so much money, an
d
 then we used to send - little things out you know, and of course I used to say to them, now, next time you write just say just what you do want, you know, and - you - you - you write and tell me and of course some of the things they asked for - would - w
o
uld sound silly to some people, but it's what they - what they wanted, what they missed you see, what they missed you know, because they weren't - as I say, they weren't like the - we did write to some - prisoners of war, who were - you know, had to exist
 
on Red Cross parcels and things like that, but the interned men weren't - weren't sort of - bodily - you know, I mean they - they had sufficient food and that sort of thing, and I believe the - Danes or wherever it was where they were interned - I believe
 
they were quite good to them, you know, but of course as I say they - they had no freedom you see and - you know, that was it, until they escaped and - I think - I think sometimes, you know, they - they almost turned a blind eye you know, in - in things o
f
 that kind. But you see with the - with the German - prisoners of war, of course - things were very different and - and one had to be very careful, and then of course you see - another thing - their - their letters - they couldn't be quite so - free in - 
