 advice of the Post Office and - people like that and all sorts of things, but you see a lot of things apart from the Red Cross didn't get through. And often the Red Cross things didn't get through, so that - you know, the whole thing was a waste of time.
 
Every - Wednesday towards the latter end of the - not the latter end - the - middle of the - war - while I was still at school - we used to - used to go to Lord Robert's Memorial - place, it's still there, the - the workshop I mean in the Brompton Road, i
t
's still in the same place, and we used to roll bandages. Make bandages and, you know, little things like that we used to do for the war effort, but we used to like to do that because you see we got - you got a couple of hours off from school you see. Use
d
 to go - used to go after lunch break on the Wednesday and then we didn't have to go back you see. We didn't have to go back but we had to sort of - book in at this place you know to see we didn't go off on our won, and stop there and do these bandages or
 
whatever they wanted us to do, it was mostly roll bandages, and things of that kind, which stood as - and that was - and that was - you know that was part of our war effort, about six of us older girls used to go and do that every week. And then - occasio
nally, about once a month we used to go up to St Dunstan}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15597842\charrsid1069857 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
s and we used to push out the blind - men in the - in the wheelchairs. And - and that was another thing where we got the time off from school you see. And -
