at - what - what you call the working class which - which - which - which I think is - is - is - is a very good description, after all's said and done I mean - you do reckon to work or you have to work at - at something or another. Well then there were th
e
 - the - then it came to the sort of - business people. Then it went on to professional people, you see, if your father was a doctor or dentist or what have you I mean you were really - you were really in the top grade then. And I may tell you he had one 
o
r two - people like that at our school also, because you see it was so well thought of that - up to the age of - say twelve or - such an age, you see, the - the tuition was - was considered good enough, and then, if they so wanted, they could send their c
h
ild to a boarding school - you know, after - and a lot of them did that, a lot of them were quite - well, to us, you know, what we called the nobs you know, they were sort of better off. But, as children you see, children - are all the world over - there 
-
 there is no class distinction with children you see. You'll find that. The same as - I think half the troubles in the world could be cleared up - if it was left with children - and - and left in that way, because you see, there'd be no racial - there'd b
e
 no - no any - thing, because a child is a child and you see, children accept each other, you see, and - and another thing about children is, you see, they're very - they're very clever really, in finding out the wrong 'uns you know. Really and truly aren
'
t they. I mean, we - we all know that - that - that - that - in a group of children you're - you're bound to find one that - that - that wants to be - you know - a little more - perhaps courageous or do a little - something perhaps he shouldn't and that s
ort of thing, and you always find children that will follow someone like that there's always perhaps be a leader of some sort hasn't there. But - I think the average - average child is - is really - pretty - pretty cute really you know. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 What would your mother and father say if another child hit you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
Well - well - first of - first of all they'd say, well what did you - did you - did you say anything to them? You see. Then you'd repeat the - the - what you'd said and what you didn't say you se
e, and that sort of thing you see, and they'd say, oh well - I think it was just - just as much your fault you see. But if it was an unprovoked - sort of attack you see, and of course we were very keen - I was as the eldest, on anybody attacking any of my
 
young - younger ones you see, and of course if - of course you always get a bully somewhere or other you see, and the best way the best way to cope with a bully is to - you know - to sort of give him as good as he gets you see. Well, it's very difficult i
f
 you're a girl, and a rather puny girl at that, but of course there's more way - there's more way than one - of getting back - at - at a boy, I mean - you don't have to rely on - on - power and blows and that sort of thing, there's other ways. And believe
 
- believe it or not I knew them. And - I - I - I think I could - I could cope. I don't think I was ever frightened of anything you know. I - I mean, if I was it was very much inside me you know and I would - like disguise it to the top, but - I - I - I th
ink I - I could stand up for myself pretty well in spite of everything. I think mother too got a shock about me really you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Would you ever bring friends home from school or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Yes. Oh yes, yes, quite often, yes. Yes. Oh yes. It wasn't -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 What about birthdays, what would happen then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
Oh yes, always used to reckon to - try and have a birthday party, even if - you know, we were really fairly hard up you know, but - we - we used to try, and as I say, I used to, you know
, try and - make things as - as nice as I could you know, and - and I always used to - always used - used to like to do as a child, of course it's done quite a lot now - nowadays, I always used to like to make little individual jellies and things. 'Cos in
 
- in my day I mean a child's party was - was - jellies, blancmanges, things like that, it's all gone out now I mean they want potato crisps and sausages on sticks and things like that you see, but in those days I mean - the idea of a child's party was bun
s
 - bread and jam sandwiches - perhaps a birthday cake and - things like jellies, blancmanges, things of that kind you see, and I used to make all these - these various - little jellies, you know, individual ones, that everybody - every child had it - its 
i
ndividual one, you see, and that used to go down much better believe me than a big bowl, which my mother would be inclined to make you see, and you have a couple of spoonfuls out put on - on your plate you see. You had your own, you had your own spoons, y
o
ur own things and - and that - that used to - be - and then I used to try and save up when there was one of the boys parties, not so much for my own, but when it was them because they were always smaller children of course and I used to save up so that - 
