here used to be either an orange or an apple, by the side of the plate, for afterwards, and a little bag of sweets, then I used to divide little - you know, just little tiny - games, you know, that they could - have like - passing the - parcel along and t
h
ings like that kind you know, and - and of course - so that somebody had - well obviously in their only one can win each time, you know, the one where the parcel lands you see. So I used to make up little things, you know, very trivial little things, but 
s
o that - whether they'd won or not at the games, every child, before it left, after the party, had a little - something and I used to get - get - buy this sort of crepe paper stuff you know, and - make - make little - parcels of - of things tied up with t
h
is paper and - string or tape or something you know, pretty or - if it was for the girls used to try and find some of me - dolls things, hair ribbons and that sort of thing and tie up, and - everybody as they went out - they either had an orange to take h
o
me or an apple - after they'd had their tea and meal, and then either a little bag of sweets or a little tiny - parcel with - some little thing in you know, if it was - just a - that everybody had something. And do you know, it was very funny, I - I once 
h
eard - two or three very very young children - and - talking, and apparently there was another child in the street that had a birthday the same day as one of my little brothers you see. So they said, and they were both at the same time, we always used to 
r
eckon about three to four you know, mum said, you know, get the kids off quick you know - so, about three or half past three to four and of course you start teatime straight away you know. And - and these children were discussing - which they were going y
