\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 How often would they come up to stay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Oh they - we - we - we had th
em with us for about two months. I think it's the only - only time, you know, my mother - my mother ever really got cross and of course she couldn't get cross with them so she used to get cross with you know. It was - yes, it was - well it was - it was to
o much, you see they - you see, when - you - when you try with children that have never been disciplined it's very hard, you see, when they're somebody else's children it's very difficult you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Can you remember whether your father ever had any political interest at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
Well - of course he was a - he was a Lloyd George man. Yes, he was a Liberal. My mother was always - always Conservative. I don't think they argued about that really, but I mean - you see, they just stuck to what they thought y
ou see, I mean, dad didn't say - you know, oh I think you ought to be a Liberal, you see, in - in those days - which was rather wonderful I think because in those days really, I mean, the - average working woman, I mean, she was whatever her husband was, 
I
 mean, she probably didn't know a thing about you know politics which - you know, perhaps is all to the good, but - you know, you - if your husband was a - a Labour man say, or what have you, well you were automatically one. But you see, my mother - my mo
t
her didn't you see when dad used to pass out about Lloyd George and that, the Liberal - party and all this, that and the other, she used to say, oh well, you - you - you think what you - think and I think what I think, you know, and I'm going to be - so a
n
d so. Well of course when it got time, you know - when I got older you know to be - have a vote and that sort of thing you see, dad used to very craftily say to me, well I think the Liberal people you know have got the best chance, you know, I used to wai
v
er between the two, which I still do. But I'm - I'm really rather sorry, although I'm at heart a Conservative if I'm anything, and - and - but I'm very sorry for the Liberal people because - I fell that if only they could get up in enough strength, I thin
k that they've got the best of both - parties, myself. You know, as much as I know about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Were you ever interested in politics yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Not really. No, not really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 I don't suppose your mother could vote in elections before 1918 but did your father actually go along and vote?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Oh yes, they used to vote. Oh yes, he'd vote. As I say, they'd - they'd both go up to the - you know - polling booth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Could women vote in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Well - a bit later on probably I'm talking of now, yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Did he take part in any political activities like canvassing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
No. No. No, I don't think he - I don't think he was committed as much as all that, but - you know, I mean if anybody was talking, you know, say, don't say to me, he's 
only a so and so Communist or something like that you know. He - he had - he had views about that, you know, he didn't - he didn't quite care about that sort of thing but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Why do you think he was a Liberal?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 I don't know, I suppose - well I sup
pose he - he felt that the - at the time they'd got the best policy. Of course I mean - I mean - as far as Lloyd George is concerned I mean I suppose he - like a lot of these politicians I suppose he had a lot of good points. There's a lot of things that 
-
 that - that were right. I mean, he - he did bring out - he did bring out the - what do you call it - National Health business didn't he, he did start it. And - he started quite a lot of things and I mean he - he - you see, why - why I think my father was
 
keen on Lloyd George - he - he'd been - he'd been a miner's son, and he was a - you know, he was really basically a - a - you know a working man's - you know - I mean, he'd got on but I mean he was actually a working - man, whereas most of the - most of t
h
e - Conservatives of that period were - either out of the peerage or - what have you or - you know somebody that in my dad's capacity hadn't done that much - you know, themselves, I mean, they were born in - born whatever they were you see. Whereas my mot
h
er, you see, she dealt so much with - the so called gentry that she felt that she knew - that side of it too you see. And - as - as she always said, she said, well it's so silly of these Communist people to say about everybody being equal, because, she sa
i
d, if we were all equal today - somebody is going to have a bit more than you've got tomorrow because that's only human nature, and it is true. I had cousins that were very great on being - and - and as they got on and progressed you know - one day - when
 
she came to see us you know, they'd got this beautiful house that they'd bought and one thing and another and she was talking about an au pair girl you see. So my mother said tohher, well - what do you want a new pair girl for? She said, to look after the
 
children. So mother, said, oh, but she said, you don't believe in that surely, she said, everybody's as good - she said, why should she come and work for you? So she looked a hit abashed so she said, well - why shouldn't she if I can pay her? So mum said,
 
well - how can you pay her if we're all equal? She said, you don't practice what you preach. She said, if - if we're all equal, she said, I - I', not saying we are but you - you - you've always said it, and you've always stuck up for it, she said, we're a
ll equal like that, she said, she's just as good as you, she said, she shouldn't have to come and mind your children, you should mind your own children. She didn't like it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 In some cases if the employee voted differently to the employer ...........?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
Oh yes. Yes. Oh, of course there was a lot of that in the very early days, I mean you automatically had to be whatever your boss was, I mean that was - that was the thing you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Did your father have any pressure like that put on him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 I don
't think so, I don't think so, I think he must have - but you see, he never had - he never had bosses in the same - same way as my mother did you see, because it was quite different. I mean, it was more of an impartial thing, you see, and it didn't it did
n
't last, I mean, my - my father, apart from the time when he went to Harrods, he was about twelve years at Harrods altogether, but - but apart from the time he went there I mean, he - he - he probably hadn't had a job for more than about a year or so, at 
a
 time, you see. Not because there was anything - you know - probably the man's business didn't - flourish or - something of that kind, or - or - you know - or or he wanted a Frenchman or he wanted a - an Italian or - or something of that, or he was bought
 out by somebody else or - expanded and - you know, didn't -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Your mother worked for gentry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Would she live in when she wasn't abroad?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Oh yes, of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 When she wasn't abroad would she live in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Oh she wouldn't - oh - oh no, she wouldn't - oh no, she wouldn't live in. She'd be home, yes, oh yes, she'd be home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 What kind of people did she work for, what line were they in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Well - all - all depends what was wanted doing you know and what was necessary to be doin
g you know. They were mostly people that had known people that mother had been with, you know, for years, you know, that was the sort of thing, she used to mostly go for the day and - it was mostly to do lady's maids work you know and of course as the - a
s
 the time got on it got less - you know - well got more difficult rather - for for people to - to employ sort of servants. You see, they - nowadays there - there's very few houses where they've got the full implicate you know, they haven't got - butler an
d
 - footmen, you see, and in the days I'm talking about, like my brother I mean - when - some time after he couldn't get any work - for a little while, he went - he went as valet to the Duke of Portland. Well there were forty servants. You see, and he had 
his own rooms, I've seen them, I've been there, he had his own rooms and he had servants to wait on him. You see, that was - that was the position of - of - of things in those days you see. They had servants waiting on servants you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 You said there were the professional, the business and the working class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 What group do you think your family belonged to at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Oh I think we were working class, I think we always considered ourselves working class. And there was no stigma a
ttached to that, I mean - that wasn't anything - out of the way to be working class I mean -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Do you think there were different levels inside the working class?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Probably. Probably so, yes. Yes. Yes. Then of course it comes business. Business - y
ou know, the little business man you know, you know, little man with a little business you see, that was a sort of a first rung up sort of thing, you know, that's when you - first sort of got ideas. Well then of course it - then it got to owning your own 
h
ouse. Which of course was another - step up if you could manage it you see. And then of course - started coming this all hire purchase business where - nobody waited for years and years 'til they could afford something, they just simply got it and - and p
a
id for it when they could you see. But of course, that - that was always ignored as far as we were concerned, I mean, what we - what we couldn't afford we didn't have and - and - probably I mean we didn't have as - you know - what shall I say - up to date
 homes as - as a - and - and quite frankly I would never want one. That's why you see I've got quite a few antiques. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 So it was possible to move up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Oh yes. Yes. Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Was it possible to move down as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Well - oh quite -
 quite - quite easily I should imagine, I mean - you know - it's a quite easy to - to not do something for some time and - you know - and be out on your - on your ear sort of thing you know. But I - I think it was - it's all - I mean, the - the great thin
g
 was to try and have a trade if you could, I mean if you had a trade you were - more or less never out of work for very long. But of course - there was so many unskilled people - about - through no fault of their own - and - and - and of course when their
 jobs - you know - were just - you know, non-existent well then - they - there was just nothing for them you see and there was very little relief for people like that, was very - very sad really you know. And of course you -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Were there people like that around Chelsea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
Oh quite a lot, quite a lot. Quite a lot. In the old days I should say - yes. Oh I should say - fifty percent - probably. Yes, quite. Quite. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 What was peoples attitude towards families like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Well - you know - of c
ourse there - there was always certain people that will always - always go - you know - and ask for things, and you see and there's always - the other people - the other sort that - you know, will die first sort of thing you see, I think we belonged to th
a
t category you know. I think the idea of asking for anything you know, would - you know, as I say there was all that sort of charity element you know, that was the feeling that one got you see, and that was the feeling I'm afraid you know, although it's y
e
ars ago, that was the feeling that they gave to people, that they were - you know, they were asking and - and - and getting charity you know and - you know, were the sort of the thing, you had - you had to be very hard faced to do it you know, you had to 
have a very thick skin, it was no good being sensitive on - on - on those - terms you know. No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Did your father go to any other clubs apart from the cycling?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 No. No, they were mostly cycling clubs he went to. But various ones he went to you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Did he ever used to go the races, you said he used to bet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
Oh yes, yes, yes, oh yes, he used to go there. Of course some - sometimes he used to go down - you know - with a catering firm, you know in - in that capacity you know, like - that use
d to please him very much you know. Oh yes, he's been to Ascot and - various places. Of course mother's - mother's also - been to races but - not because she was interested in the horses but because - you know, they - they probably did that sort of thing,
 
the same as - various people she was with were - went - shooting you know, had a shooting box up in Scotland and that sort of thing you know, she'd be up there. For that same reason you see. No, I think life is a great deal what you - what you make of it 
or what you can make of it, and you, can make, you know, quite a lot I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Did you ever know of any families that got ruined by drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Well, yes, unfortunately it was - it was there because you see - drink was very cheap in those days you see 
and - and of course if you're not of a very - what shall I say, you know - emotionally and otherwise not very strong, I mean - you know, it was - I suppose it was one of the ways of sort of drowning your sorrows as it were you see and it was quite a - it 
w
as quite a thing, I mean, people didn't - well, they more or less I think - it was expected, especially men that did labouring sort of work you know. And costermongers, they were expected to have a very big capacity you know for - for drink and that sort 
o
f thing and - and - oh yes, I can remember the old days in the - in the - the Wilton Street police station, it's now where the traffic wardens go, I see it's still there, but I can remember them wheeling the drunks in you know and of course all us kids, w
e
 used to run up behind, you know, we used to think it was great fun you know, we couldn't realize these poor souls you know - we - 'cos they used - they used to - used to do some funny antics you know, they used to have to more or less strap them onto thi
s
 - stretcher thing to get them along, you know, the policemen you see. And then we used to watch the old black maria, we used to always feel sorry for people going in on Saturday nights you see, because they were all there Sunday, and the black maria used
 
to come round Monday morning to take them off to the courts you see. And - we - we always used to try and get round there you know before it got - you know, on - on our way to school and that to see if we could - see the black maria going, it used to go a
b
out half past eight. And we used to get round there about half past eight to watch the black maria going off to count how many - you know, were going off, well of course by that time they - if they were drunk you see they'd more or less sobered up, they'd
 
had all - all Saturday and the rest of Saturday night in the cell and they'd had all - all day Sunday you see, and probably only had a cup of tea or something you know, don't know what the police used to give them, then of course they'd go up, you know, f
o
r the - court on Sunday. And I - I've - I - I've been going to school once and I - I - I - I told mother about it afterwards, I thought, oh isn't it a shame mum, I was going to school with one girl and of course her father was in this, she was, saying goo
d
 bye dad, as if he was going off to a picnic you know, and of course he'd - he'd got over his drunken about but he was a - he was what they called one of the regulars, he was always in this - this man you know. Goodbye dad, she was waving you know as if h
e was going off on a picnic, the poor man was going off to - you know, I - I don't - I don't think, you know, that they did anything very much you know, they probably -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Were policemen very much in evidence in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Oh yes, but - of course 
round here there was one or two very rough quarters in the - in - in my younger days, and - they used to go two at a time. They daren't go around on their own, no, they were frightened - and of course - it - it's a funny thing you should say that you know
,
 nowadays, they say it's one of the signs of growing old, but nowadays policemen look so jolly young. In my day - I - the policemen, the average policeman was always about thirty, like to being with you know. And the police sergeants of course were always
 
- you know - old chaps sort of thing you know. But - I don't know, somehow, they gave you - they gave you a lot of confidence and of course there was no traffic lights and I mean and we were always - always taught always even when it was horse traffic or 
w
hat have you, we were always taught to - never to try to run across a road, always to wait for the policeman. And of course which we always did. And - and my mother always taught us, which I think was very wise, that - you know - if - if we were lost or i
f
 we were frightened or anything - anytime we were out you know - to always - go and ask a policeman, you know, never to stop and ask a passer by in case - it was somebody you know, that shouldn't be you know, and I think it's very good, I think it was ver
y
 silly because a lot of people in those days used to frighten children about policemen you know, they used to say to them you know, if you're not good I'll get the policeman round after you, you know, I - I'll get the policeman to talk to you and - he'dll
 
take you off and all that sort of thing, and it - you see, in some little one's minds you know that - that would be sort of a bogey element, which I think was wrong because I mean, the average policeman is generally a very - friendly sort of chap you know
,
 well specially our policemen I mean they are aren't they, all - all the world over. And - you know, I - I think that we had the right idea because we - we'd never be frightened if we - if - if we did get anywhere out of our depth a bit and we were a bit 
-
 or felt we were - didn't quite know where we were, I mean, we'd - make a bee line, and of course in those days you see you always saw them at the various - you know, what do you call it, stopping places you see. And of course they were always - round on 
t
he beat, I mean you hardly see a policeman on the beat these days do you, I mean they're either in Panda cars or what have you. But in those days you see, they used to do regular beats and at regular times and of course you - you know. You got to know. An
d of course we would always go up to a policeman and, you know, say -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 You say there were some rough areas around here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Oh very rough.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Were some families thought of as rough and some as respectable in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Yes, well they - they 
- they were - there were quite - quite a few of - of the rougher elements but - you see, when I say rough I mean I don't think - I - I mean they weren't - snatch and grabbers and they wouldn't have - have beaten us up or anything like that. I don't say wh
at they might have done to anybody - you know, better off than us, but I mean they - they wouldn't have harmed us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Was there any distinction between labourers and craftsmen in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Oh yes. Oh yes. Yes. Oh yes, if - if - if your - if your d
ad had a - had - you know, got a sort of trade and that sort of thing you know I mean - you were - you were really one up on the kids whose - whose - whose father -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Did your father do an apprenticeship period for being a chef?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Well I suppose he 
must have done, I don't remember when it was but I suppose he must have done. I mean, he couldn't have taught himself all he knew. I don't remember, you know, that's one of the things I - I - I don't seem to be very - you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 You think your mother saw herself as belonging to a particular social group?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
No, not particularly but - but my - my mother couldn't bear what she called communists. She always said, there's no need to be common. You might be poor but you - you - you need - you needn't be c
ommon, there's no need - and there's no need to speak - that - that was another thing, she didn't like - she didn't like this - well I - I - I mean I - I shudder sometimes when I hear some of the children round here, that they - they don't speak - you see
,
 they don't teach them, they teach them phonetically or something at school now don't they? I don't know. I told - I - I - I said to my niece when she was coming, she said, oh well we don't do it like that now auntie. I said, well no, perhaps you don't, b
u
t, I said, I don't think it's right what you do do. It doesn't seem to give the children the same - and they do speak very badly. Probably because their parents - speak the same you see and of course, to a child, I mean what your parents - do is - you kno
w
, is - is the thing to do isn't it really. You see, that's why I mean a lot of these little ones round here I mean you hear them - using most terrible swear words you know, I - I stopped one little boy once, I said, you mustn't say that, that's naughty. S
o
 he said, oh can't be very naughty, my dad says it. So I said, yes, I expect your dad does say it, but still that - you see, the child - I mean - you know they - they don't realize children, say most awful things. No, I don't think it's - it's very nice, 
I don't think it's -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Can you remember in those days anybody that you thought, oh she's a real lady, or that's a real gentleman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Well it's something that instinctively you see - that instinctively you know. It's - it's a very strange thing, becau
se - I don't know - I don't know how to express it but - if you meet - you know, what my mother would term a lady or a gentleman, it has nothing to do with - attire, nothing to do with clothing, nothing to do with that but directly they speak to you you k
n
ow. It's something to do with manners I think. I think that's something to do with manners. And I think that's something that's been ridiculed to such an extent that - that the majority of people - you know - they think it's just funny. But I don't think 
it is. I don't think good manners is - is - is ever - is ever a waste. No, I don't think so. I don't think so. -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Were you ever told to curtsey or show respect in any way to people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Oh well only, of course we - you know, at the school we used to v
ery often have - you know - old - Princess Marie Louise and - very old Princess and - one or two of the older Princesses come and of course we always had to do our curtsey you see. And - and that sort of thing, but - no, I think that had - that had began 
to go out and you know you didn't touch your forelock and things like that kind. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 What about things like calling people sir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Sir. Yes, well that I think is a very good thing. I think - I still think - and - and you still, if you - if you lis
ten sometimes, you will still hear - quite grown men call their father's sir. Which I think - I think is - that is - is something rather nice really myself. I - I - I don't think you - I mean, a lot of people will say, oh sissy and all, well I don't think
 
so. I - I - I don't see that it is. I think it's - I think it's something rather nice. I think - I think a certain respect - mind you, I mean - if you're going back to Victorian times, well then I think they did carry it a little bit too far. I mean you p
robably - you know - sort of the Barrat\rquote 
s of Wimpole Street touch you know, you - you had to be, you know, the - they were far too much kept down. No, I mean you want - want a happy medium but I - I - I think - I think respect for parents is - is - is a gre
at thing. And I did respect my parents, and - you know, I - I think that - so much trouble nowadays you see - there is no respect, you see, they don't - they don't seem to - merit respect and they don't get it. You see, which - which I think is a shame. '
C
os after all, whatever they are or whatever they've been - they are your parents. And I mean whether you've made good - which lots of people have, that's why I'm a great admirer of Tommy Steele, and people of his kind, because he never forgets, or not for
 
very long, that he was once a poor boy, he never forgets the people that he - he came from, which I - I don't think you - you should do, but you see, unfortunately you do see too much of the other, and I mean, I've known - I've known people of my age that
 
have grown up and have been ashamed of their parents I'm sorry to say. And - and - and they've been parents like my parents, and brought them up and - given them as much as they could - educational wise and - and things of that kind you know, and even don
e perhaps more than my parents did, even sent them - I mean, I know of one girl, that her parents sacrificed quite a lot to send her to Pitman\rquote 
s to learn shorthand which you had to pay for yourself you know, and - and quite a lot and I mean they hadn't much
 money and - and then they'd - and she got on, certainly, but she got on. But then she got that - she found little faults in her parents and that sort of thing and it got on to such an extent that she didn't visit her parents, and - and things - well that
 
- that I - I - I don't call that getting - 'cos she did say to somebody once, oh well, now I've got up in the world I've got to forget those times. But - I don't - I don't think so, I don't think that's getting on in the world, I don't think she's got on 
i
n the world. She has in material things, she's got money, but I don't think - I don't think to know that her - her parents - you know, are sort of living on assistance and - and - and - needn't be, because - she could quite well - I don't think that's - t
hat's to the good. Not - not to my way of thinking. But still that's only me.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 What kind of people would be the teachers and the clergymen and tradespeople, what kind of groups would they belong to in those days?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Oh well, the - the - well - clerg
ymen of course always come under the professional heading you see. See, a clergyman, a doctor, dentist, people of that kind - they - they - they were always - you know, sort of - on the up-grade, you know, they were coming up sort of thing you know.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 How about teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
Well teachers - teachers had a pretty good - you know, pretty fair, we always - always - always - respected a teacher I mean you know I mean - if you knew of anybody who was marrying a teacher you know you thought they'd gone up in
 the world, but of course even in those days if you married, I mean, several of my friends did marry policemen, well I mean that wasn't a bad job considering, in those days you see. But of course a soldier, that wasn't considered quite so good you see. It
's - it's very funny the way - the way - things decree you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Who would be the most important people in the area you lived in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Well, not exactly important I shouldn't think but more - like solicitors - you know, lawyers, solicitors, doctors, d
entists, you know. People -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 What kind of people went to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
Well I think - I think they come from all - all - but I - I'll say one thing about the average working people, they probably didn't ever go to church themselves a lot of them. But t
hey nearly always sent their children, and sent their children to Sunday school. And some of them, I mean I think they did a bit too much because they sent them two and three times on a Sunday.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Did you just go the ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 I usually went twice. Usually.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 In the evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Do you think policemen treated the people well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
Oh I think so. Oh yes, there was a very good relationship you know - among them. Very good. I mean, as I said they had their old regulars, and if they could -
 I mean if - if a man could - reasonably stand up and they knew where he lived you know, even if he had had a drop too much, I mean they would - they would - more or less take him home, you know, and - push him in. If - if - if he didn't start - on the ar
guments and what have you see. Oh yes, they were very good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Was your home rented in these days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
Oh yes, yes, always rented, oh yes, we never - we never had a home of our own, I think it was a great disappointment to my mother but - as I say, my f
ather was - if anything he was too contented. You see, if he got a certain amount, he felt that - he - he was all right, he never thought of the times when he didn't get anything. You see. So -;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Did he belong to a sick club or a boot club or a savings club of any kind?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 
No, he didn't - he - he wasn't very keen on insurances, that's why my mother always - always got us insured and that, though - yes, and I - I know - we had a laugh once, he says, well it's not right, he said, you've got me insured 
for more than - you know, you've - you're insured for, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033865 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 What were the landlords like, were they fair?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232920 AH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2569466\charrsid1069857 Well I think so, long as you paid your rent and of course in those days it wasn't - it wasn't terribly difficult I mean if you - if you
 didn't like - you know - anything you didn't like and they wouldn't do anything for you you know, that you felt that they ought to do with repairs and what have you, well then you - you sort of - talked it over with your wife and - you walked about and -
 I mean, probably in the next street there'd be a house up you know and - you - you - you just, you know, paid up 'til the end of the week whatever it was and - and then you cleared out, I mean there wasn't much - trouble.
\par }}